For Q2, we have 10 prime numbers. They are all between 100 and 200. Are they all primes? Yes. But maybe they are all primes that are also something else? For example, they might be primes that are 1 mod 4? Let's check modulo 4:

103 mod 4 = 3 (since 100 mod4=0, 3 mod4=3)
101 mod4 = 1
197 mod4 = 1 (196 is 49*4, so 197 mod4=1)
151 mod4 = 3 (148=37*4, 151-148=3)
127 mod4 = 3 (124=31*4, 127-124=3)
137 mod4 = 1 (136=34*4, 137-136=1)
179 mod4 = 3 (176=44*4, 179-176=3)
199 mod4 = 3 (196=49*4, 199-196=3)
191 mod4 = 3 (188=47*4, 191-188=3)
109 mod4 = 1 (108=27*4, 109-108=1)

So we have both 1 mod4 and 3 mod4. Not all same.

Maybe they are all primes that are not of the form 4k+1? But we have 101,197,137,109 which are 1 mod4. So no.

Maybe they are all primes that are safe primes? A safe prime is a prime p such that (p-1)/2 is also prime. Check: For 103, (103-1)/2=51, not prime. So not safe. 101: (101-1)/2=50, not prime. 197: (197-1)/2=98, not prime. 151: (151-1)/2=75, not prime. 127: (127-1)/2=63, not prime. 137: (137-1)/2=68, not prime. 179: (179-1)/2=89, prime? 89 is prime. So 179 is a safe prime? Actually safe prime definition: p is safe if p=2q+1 where q is prime. So for 179, q=89 prime, so yes, 179 is a safe prime. But others? 199: (199-1)/2=99, not prime. 191: (191-1)/2=95, not prime. 109: (109-1)/2=54, not prime. So only 179 is safe. So not all.

Maybe they are all primes that are Sophie Germain primes? A Sophie Germain prime is a prime p such that 2p+1 is also prime. Check: For 103, 2*103+1=207, not prime. 101: 203, not prime. 197: 395, not prime. 151: 303, not prime. 127: 255, not prime. 137: 275, not prime. 179: 359, is 359 prime? 359, check: not divisible by 2,3,5,7: 7*51=357, 359-357=2; 11: 11*32=352, remainder 7; 13: 13*27=351, remainder 8; 17: 17*21=357, remainder 2; 19: 19*18=342, remainder 17; so 359 is prime. So 179 is Sophie Germain? Actually Sophie Germain prime p means 2p+1 is prime. For p=179, 2*179+1=359, which is prime, so yes, 179 is Sophie Germain. But others? 199: 399, not prime. 191: 383, is 383 prime? 383, check: 2,3,5,7: 7*54=378, 383-378=5; 11: 11*34=374, remainder 9; 13: 13*29=377, remainder 6; 17: 17*22=374, remainder 9; 19: 19*20=380, remainder 3; so 383 is prime? Actually 383: 383/17=22.52, 17*22=374, remainder 9; 19*20=380, remainder 3; 23*16=368, remainder 15; so yes, 383 is prime. So 191 is also Sophie Germain? 2*191+1=383, prime. So 191 is Sophie Germain. 109: 2*109+1=219, not prime. So not all.

